ChatGPT said:

I see what you‚Äôre trying to implement ‚Äî this is LeetCode 1769: Minimum Number of Operations to Move All Balls to Each Box.

The idea is to compute, for each box, how many operations (ball moves) are needed to bring all balls into that box.

Issues with your code:

left and right are not computed correctly:

Multiplying by 2 is wrong ‚Äî the cost should increase by +1 per shift of distance, not doubling.

You‚Äôre trying to reuse the same loop for left and right, but that‚Äôs making indices tricky.

You should do two passes:

Left-to-right pass: accumulate cost from left side.

Right-to-left pass: accumulate cost from right side.

Correct Approach
vector<int> minOperations(string boxes) {
    int n = boxes.size();
    vector<int> left(n, 0), right(n, 0), ans(n, 0);

    // left pass
    int balls = (boxes[0] == '1'); 
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        left[i] = left[i-1] + balls; // move previous balls one step right
        if (boxes[i] == '1') balls++;
    }

    // right pass
    balls = (boxes[n-1] == '1');
    for (int i = n-2; i >= 0; i--) {
        right[i] = right[i+1] + balls; // move balls one step left
        if (boxes[i] == '1') balls++;
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        ans[i] = left[i] + right[i];
    }
    return ans;
}

Walkthrough Example

boxes = "110"

Left pass:

left = [0,1,2]

Right pass:

right = [2,1,0]

Answer = [2,2,2]

üëâ So the fix is:

Don‚Äôt multiply by 2.

Use two passes (left‚Üíright, right‚Üíleft).

Do you want me to also show you how to optimize to O(1) extra space (without left/right arrays), since only running sums are needed?

